math_2044.solution:
In general, the real part of a complex number $z$ is given by
\[\frac{z + \overline{z}}{2}.\]Hence, the real part of $1/z$ is equal to 1/6 if and only if
\[\frac{\frac{1}{z} + \frac{1}{\overline{z}}}{2} = \frac{1}{6},\]or
\[\frac{1}{z} + \frac{1}{\overline{z}} = \frac{1}{3}.\]Multiplying both sides by $3z \overline{z}$, we get
\[3z + 3 \overline{z} = z \overline{z}.\]We can re-write this equation as
\[z \overline{z} - 3z - 3 \overline{z} + 9 = 9.\]The left-hand side factors as
\[(z - 3)(\overline{z} - 3) = 9.\]Since $\overline{z} - 3$ is the conjugate of $z - 3$, this equation becomes
\[|z - 3|^2 = 9.\][asy]
unitsize(0.5 cm);

draw(Circle((3,0),3),red);
draw((-0.5,0)--(6.5,0));
draw((0,-3)--(0,3));
filldraw(Circle((0,0),0.1),white,red);

label("Re", (6.5,0), NE);
label("Im", (0,3), NE);
dot("$3$", (3,0), N);
[/asy]

Hence, $S$ is the set of complex numbers that have a distance of 3 from the complex number 3 (except 0).  This is a circle of radius 3, so the area of the region inside is $\boxed{9 \pi}$.

math_1925.solution:
Since $\cot^{-1} \left( \frac{1}{x} \right) = \tan^{-1} x$ for all $x,$ we can write
\[\sin \left( 2 \tan^{-1} x \right) = \frac{1}{3}.\]Let $\theta = \tan^{-1} x,$ so $x = \tan \theta.$  Also, $\sin 2 \theta = \frac{1}{3},$ so
\[2 \sin \theta \cos \theta = \frac{1}{3}.\]Construct a right triangle with legs 1 and $x.$  Then the angle opposite the side length $x$ be $\theta.$

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, B, C;

A = (2,1.8);
B = (0,0);
C = (2,0);

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(rightanglemark(A,C,B,8));

label("$\theta$", B + (0.7,0.3));
label("$1$", (B + C)/2, S);
label("$x$", (A + C)/2, E);
label("$\sqrt{x^2 + 1}$", (A + B)/2, NW);
[/asy]

Also, the hypotenuse will be $\sqrt{x^2 + 1},$ so $\cos \theta = \frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2 + 1}}$ and $\sin \theta = \frac{x}{\sqrt{x^2 + 1}}.$  Hence,
\[2 \cdot \frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2 + 1}} \cdot \frac{x}{\sqrt{x^2 + 1}} = \frac{1}{3},\]or
\[\frac{2x}{x^2 + 1} = \frac{1}{3}.\]This gives us $x^2 + 1 = 6x,$ or $x^2 - 6x + 1 = 0.$  By the quadratic formula, the roots are $x = \boxed{3 \pm 2 \sqrt{2}}.$

